ndu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cocton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name mostly from Coston (Norfolk), though there are similarly named places in Shropshire and Leicestershire.","English: variant of   Costin  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>coste</i> ‘slope’ or ‘river bank, coast’ (see   Cote  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Costin","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Costin</i>, <i>Costein</i>, a shortened form of Old French   Constantine  , Anglo-Norman French <i>Costetin</i>, from Latin <i>Constantinus</i>.","English, Scottish, and Manx: in northwestern England it may be a variant of Manx   Costain  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Cocton was born in 1196, in Coughton, Warwickshire, England. She married William Marney after February 1236. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1236, in her hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1196–1236":"1196–1236","1192–1236":"1192–1236","–1263":"–1263","1214–1235":"1214–1235","1217–Female":"1217–Surnud","–1235":"–1235","–1241":"–1241","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1196":"1196","1192":"1192","after 1214":"pärast 1214","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1214":"1214","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","1235":"1235","1277":"1277","after 1235":"pärast 1235","Coughton, Warwickshire, England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Goldington, Oxfordshire, England":"Goldington, Bedfordshire, England","Warwick, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1196–1236":"1196–1236","1192–1236":"1192–1236","–1263":"–1263","1214–1235":"1214–1235","1217–Female":"1217–Kuollut","–1235":"–1235","–1241":"–1241","1277–Male":"1277–Kuollut","1279–Male":"1279–Kuollut","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1196":"1196","1192":"1192","after 1214":"1214 jälkeen","1217